[
    {
        "content": "<p>Say <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi><mo><mover><mo><mo>→</mo></mo><mi>j</mi></mover></mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{A} \\overset{j}{\\to} \\mathcal{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.1756em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.1756em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">→</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.614em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is an inclusion of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span></span></span></span> as a subcategory of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span>. Then given a functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : \\mathcal{A} \\to \\mathcal{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span> we might want to <em>extend</em> it to a functor defined on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03041em;\">B</span></span></span></span>. The universal way to do this is called the <strong>Left Kan Extension</strong> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> along <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">j</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.854em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05724em;\">j</span></span></span></span>, and this extension tends to exist (for instance, whenever <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">A</span></span></span></span> is \"small enough\" and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.14643em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is cocomplete).</p>",
        "id": 378233928,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Grossack (they/them)",
        "timestamp": 1690222659
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Now, a (left) kan extension is called a <strong>Pointwise Kan Extension</strong> if it's one that we can really compute, for instance by a formula involving <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/end\">coends</a>.  There's a definition (given in Loregian's <em>Coend Calculus</em>) that a kan extension is pointwise exactly when it plays nice with comma categories in the sense shown in this diagram (taken from the book):</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/b6NNog-Sw_RnfPwbI_fFKjc_/Screenshot-2023-07-24-at-11.20.31-AM.png\">Screenshot-2023-07-24-at-11.20.31-AM.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/b6NNog-Sw_RnfPwbI_fFKjc_/Screenshot-2023-07-24-at-11.20.31-AM.png\" title=\"Screenshot-2023-07-24-at-11.20.31-AM.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/b6NNog-Sw_RnfPwbI_fFKjc_/Screenshot-2023-07-24-at-11.20.31-AM.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 378234691,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Grossack (they/them)",
        "timestamp": 1690222849
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My question, then, is this: </p>\n<p>Why is this called a \"pointwise\" kan extension? I might guess that it's because we can compute it \"pointwise\" with the coend formula... But this condition on comma categories is somewhat mysterious to me, and it seems like a weird choice to take as the definition</p>",
        "id": 378234869,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Grossack (they/them)",
        "timestamp": 1690222902
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, it's because of the coend formula: the value of the Kan extension functor at each object (i.e. at each <em>point</em>) can be computed with its own universal property, rather than just the entire functor having a universal property.</p>",
        "id": 378240188,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1690224182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The connection of the coend formula to the comma category definition is that if you take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X=1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> then the comma category definition tells you that the \"evaluation\" of the extension at a \"point\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k: 1 \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> has its own universal property, which expressed as a colimit (= Kan extension to 1) over that comma category, which turns out to be equivalent to the usual coend definition.</p>",
        "id": 378240658,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1690224315
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The general version is the usual sort of thing where you replace elements by generalized elements.</p>",
        "id": 378240758,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1690224343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's worth noting that the comma-category definition is equivalent to the coend-based definition in \"set-like\" 2-categories such as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Cat</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Cat</span></span></span></span></span>, or internal categories in some category with finite limits, but is <em>not</em> equivalent to it in other 2-categories such as categories enriched over some monoidal category.  In the latter case, the coend definition is the right one, not the comma category definition.  But there is an abstract version of the coend definition that makes sense in any proarrow equipment or Yoneda structure.</p>",
        "id": 378241211,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1690224444
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Why.20are.20Pointwise.20Kan.20Extensions.20called.20that.3F/near/378240658\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The connection of the coend formula to the comma category definition is that if you take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X=1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> then the comma category definition tells you that the \"evaluation\" of the extension at a \"point\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k: 1 \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> has its own universal property, which expressed as a colimit (= Kan extension to 1) over that comma category, which turns out to be equivalent to the usual coend definition.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Oooooooooooooh. That makes perfect sense, thanks ^_^</p>",
        "id": 378246409,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Grossack (they/them)",
        "timestamp": 1690225803
    },
